The most consequential development of Week 30 was the federalization of policing in the nation\'92s capital. Trump declared a \'93crime emergency\'94 in Washington, D.C., despite data showing violent crime at a thirty\uc0\u8209 year low, and issued an executive order that placed the Metropolitan Police Department at the service of federal purposes. National Guard troops were deployed on city streets. Federal agents from the FBI, ATF, DEA, ICE, and DHS were surged into the district. The administration invoked a clause of the D.C. Home Rule Act that had never before been used in this way, and Trump openly mused about overturning home rule altogether, returning the capital to direct federal control. This was not a response to a genuine breakdown in order. It was a test of how far emergency language could stretch to justify a political occupation of a disfavored jurisdiction. The winners were the executive and its security allies, who gained a precedent for treating local autonomy as contingent. The losers were D.C. residents, whose elected leaders saw their authority overridden, and the broader norm that federal power is neutral across regions.\
