The takeover did not go unchallenged. D.C.\'92s attorney general sued to block the federalization, arguing that the conditions required by the Home Rule Act had not been met and that the move endangered public safety rather than protecting it. Democratic lawmakers in Congress, led by Jamie Raskin and Eleanor Holmes Norton, introduced a joint resolution to end the federalization, insisting that no \'93special emergency\'94 justified such a step. Under legal and political pressure, the White House negotiated an agreement with D.C. officials to scale back the order. The Metropolitan Police Department would remain under the control of its chief, Pamela Smith, rather than being placed under a DEA administrator. The administration retained the power to direct local police for federal purposes in emergencies, but the most blatant form of the takeover was blunted. This partial rollback mattered. It showed that courts and Congress still had leverage, and that local actors could force the executive to retreat. Yet the episode also left a mark. It normalized the idea that a president could seize a city\'92s police force on thin pretexts, then bargain over the terms. The line had been crossed once. Crossing it again would be easier.\
